@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Project Management Overview";
    Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_Layout.cshtml";
}

<div class="container">
    <h2>Project Management Overview</h2>
    <div>
        <h3>2 Day Course</h3>

        <h4 style="margin-top: 20px;">Pre-Course Preparation </h4>

        <p>Participants will be asked to think of their experiences in a previous or current project and come prepared to share and contribute to the course.</p>

        <h4 style="margin-top: 20px;">Overview</h4>

        <p>Project environments are dynamic, fast paced and (should be) focused on delivery. The role and skillsof a project manager are varied and vital to ensuring success of a project. This interactive course will equip project managers with the effective tools you need to run a project from start to finish.</p>

        <h4 style="margin-top: 20px;">Who will this course benefit?</h4>
        <p>
            Existing Project Managers or anyone who is involved in running projects.
        </p>

        <h4 style="margin-top: 20px;">By the end of this 2 day course, you will be able to:</h4>
        <ul class="site-features">
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Clarify what a project is and how it differs from day to day business</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> State the factors which contribute to the success of failure of a project</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Describe the roles within a project and how they relate to each other</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Explain the life cycle and stage of a project</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Demonstrate the use of planning, monitoring and control tool to include: Network diagrams/PERT charts/Gantt with dependencies, time and critical path analysis/Organisational breakdown structures/Resource analysis/Check points and milestones/Cost benefit analysis</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Risk Assessment</li>
            <li><i class="fa fa-check"></i> Incorporate alterations to the original plan</li>

        </ul>

    </div>
</div>


